    <section class="analysis-section">
      <h2>Season-by-Season Analysis</h2>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 1 (22 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 20, 1999 – May 19, 2000</p>
        <p>The inaugural season introduced detectives Elliot Stabler and Olivia Benson, setting the dark, gritty tone of the series. The show quickly established itself as a powerful spinoff of the original Law & Order, tackling sensitive and complex cases with a focus on the victims. It laid the foundation for long-running character arcs and demonstrated a unique narrative style that resonated with viewers immediately.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 2 (21 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> October 20, 2000 – May 11, 2001</p>
        <p>Building on its initial success, the second season deepened the psychological exploration of the detectives and the perpetrators. Ice-T joined the cast as Detective Fin Tutuola, bringing a fresh dynamic to the squad room. The cases became more intricate, often blurring the lines between right and wrong, and challenging the legal system's ability to provide true justice for survivors of heinous crimes.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 3 (23 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 28, 2001 – May 17, 2002</p>
        <p>Season three continued to push boundaries with its storytelling, frequently incorporating ripped-from-the-headlines plots that reflected contemporary societal issues. The emotional toll of the job on Benson and Stabler became a central theme, highlighting the personal sacrifices required to work in the Special Victims Unit. The writing grew sharper, ensuring that the legal battles were just as compelling as the initial investigations.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 4 (25 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 27, 2002 – May 16, 2003</p>
        <p>With a massive 25-episode run, this season solidified the show's status as a television juggernaut. It featured a series of high-profile guest stars and explored systemic failures within the justice system. The dynamic between the detectives and the District Attorney's office, particularly ADA Alexandra Cabot, provided intense courtroom drama that perfectly balanced the harrowing police work on the streets of New York.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 5 (25 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 23, 2003 – May 18, 2004</p>
        <p>Another extended season that delved into the complex personal lives of the squad members. The departure of ADA Cabot and the introduction of Casey Novak marked a significant shift in the courtroom dynamic. Novak's aggressive, by-the-book approach contrasted sharply with the detectives' often rule-bending methods, creating compelling internal conflicts while they collectively fought against some of the most cunning criminals.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 6 (23 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 21, 2004 – May 24, 2005</p>
        <p>This season is often cited by fans as one of the strongest, featuring exceptionally tight writing and unforgettable performances. The cases were darker and more psychologically complex, requiring the detectives to navigate moral gray areas constantly. The evolution of Benson's character, particularly her growing empathy and occasional over-involvement in cases, became a defining element of the series' emotional core during this era.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 7 (22 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 20, 2005 – May 16, 2006</p>
        <p>Mariska Hargitay won an Emmy for her performance this season, cementing Olivia Benson as an iconic television character. The narrative focus remained tight on the intersection of law, morality, and human trauma. The partnership between Benson and Stabler reached new heights of intensity, as their unwavering commitment to the victims often put them at odds with their superiors and each other.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 8 (22 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 19, 2006 – May 22, 2007</p>
        <p>Season eight brought significant changes, including the temporary introduction of Detective Dani Beck while Benson was on undercover assignment. This shake-up tested Stabler and altered the squad's chemistry. When Benson returned, the renewed partnership faced fresh challenges, with cases that explored the darkest corners of human behavior and the lengths to which people will go to protect their secrets.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 9 (19 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 25, 2007 – May 13, 2008</p>
        <p>Despite a slightly shortened episode count due to the writers' strike, this season delivered incredibly potent narratives. It focused heavily on the ripple effects of crime on the families of victims and the detectives themselves. The legal battles were particularly fraught, often highlighting the flaws and loopholes in the system that sometimes allowed the guilty to walk free, adding a layer of tragic realism.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 10 (22 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 23, 2008 – June 2, 2009</p>
        <p>Reaching its milestone tenth season, the show showed no signs of slowing down. The introduction of ADA Kim Greylek provided a new adversarial energy in the precinct. The cases continued to be topical and controversial, challenging viewers' preconceptions about justice and morality. The season masterfully balanced procedural elements with deep character studies of the veteran detectives.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 11 (24 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 23, 2009 – May 19, 2010</p>
        <p>This season saw the return of ADA Alexandra Cabot, much to the delight of longtime fans, before transitioning to ADA Sonya Paxton. The rotating legal representation added unpredictability to the courtroom scenes. The cases were particularly harrowing, often dealing with the exploitation of the vulnerable, which fueled the detectives' relentless pursuit of justice and reinforced the show's core thematic mission.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 12 (24 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 22, 2010 – May 18, 2011</p>
        <p>A pivotal and historic season, as it marked the final appearances of Christopher Meloni as Detective Elliot Stabler. The tension and drama were at an all-time high, culminating in a shocking finale that forever altered the trajectory of the series. The season's cases were intense and deeply personal, serving as a fitting, if abrupt, conclusion to one of television's most famous partnerships.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 13 (23 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 21, 2011 – May 23, 2012</p>
        <p>The beginning of a new era. With Stabler gone, Detectives Nick Amaro and Amanda Rollins joined the squad, fundamentally changing the dynamic. Benson had to step up into a more prominent leadership role while grappling with the absence of her long-time partner. The show successfully reinvented itself, proving its resilience and the enduring appeal of its core premise despite major cast changes.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 14 (24 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 26, 2012 – May 22, 2013</p>
        <p>The new squad solidified its rhythm in season fourteen. The addition of ADA Rafael Barba brought a sharp, theatrical brilliance to the courtroom, elevating the legal drama significantly. The cases were complex and often involved moral ambiguity, requiring the new detectives to confront their own biases and past traumas while navigating the treacherous waters of New York's justice system.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 15 (24 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 25, 2013 – May 21, 2014</p>
        <p>This season is remembered for the harrowing William Lewis arc, which pushed Olivia Benson to her absolute physical and psychological limits. The intense serialization of this storyline was a departure from the strict procedural format and provided some of the most gripping television in the show's history. It profoundly changed Benson's character, leading to her eventual promotion and evolution as a leader.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 16 (23 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 24, 2014 – May 20, 2015</p>
        <p>Now Sergeant Benson, Olivia took command of the squad room. The transition in leadership brought new challenges, as she had to balance her investigative instincts with administrative responsibilities. The introduction of Detective Sonny Carisi added a blue-collar, earnest perspective to the team. The season expertly balanced the procedural elements with the ongoing personal development of its ensemble cast.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 17 (23 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 23, 2015 – May 25, 2016</p>
        <p>Continuing its strong run, this season tackled highly controversial and timely issues, including institutional corruption and the impact of technology on crime. The character dynamics continued to evolve, particularly the mentorship between Benson and the newer detectives. The writing remained sharp, ensuring that the show stayed relevant and engaging in an increasingly crowded television landscape.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 18 (21 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 21, 2016 – May 24, 2017</p>
        <p>Season eighteen explored the intersection of politics and justice, with cases that frequently involved high-profile figures and complex cover-ups. The squad faced intense scrutiny from both the public and internal affairs, testing their loyalty to one another and the badge. The emotional stakes were high, particularly as the detectives dealt with the personal fallout from their demanding careers.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 19 (24 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 27, 2017 – May 23, 2018</p>
        <p>A season marked by significant transitions, including the departure of ADA Barba and the introduction of Peter Stone. The legal battles became more philosophical, often debating the very nature of justice. The cases continued to reflect real-world issues, demonstrating the show's ongoing commitment to highlighting the struggles of survivors and the complexities of prosecuting sexual crimes in the modern era.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 20 (24 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 27, 2018 – May 16, 2019</p>
        <p>Tying the record for the longest-running primetime live-action series, season twenty was a monumental achievement. It celebrated the show's legacy while continuing to push forward with compelling new narratives. The cases were diverse and challenging, and the character arcs reached satisfying, if sometimes heartbreaking, conclusions. The season served as a testament to the enduring power of the series.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 21 (20 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 26, 2019 – April 23, 2020</p>
        <p>Making television history as the longest-running primetime live-action series, season twenty-one broke new ground. The transition of Detective Carisi to Assistant District Attorney shifted the entire dynamic of the show, bridging the gap between the precinct and the courtroom in a new way. Despite a season shortened by the global pandemic, it delivered powerful, emotionally resonant episodes.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 22 (16 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> November 12, 2020 – June 3, 2021</p>
        <p>Produced under unprecedented circumstances due to the COVID-19 pandemic, this shortened season confronted real-world issues head-on, including police reform and systemic racism. It also featured the highly anticipated return of Elliot Stabler, launching the spinoff series Organized Crime. The reunion between Benson and Stabler provided massive emotional payoff for long-time fans while setting up new narrative possibilities.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 23 (22 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 23, 2021 – May 19, 2022</p>
        <p>The historic 500th episode aired this season, celebrating the show's unparalleled legacy. The narrative frequently crossed over with Organized Crime, deepening the expanded Law & Order universe. The cases remained complex and topical, while the personal lives of the detectives, particularly the evolving relationship between Benson and Stabler, kept audiences deeply invested in the ongoing saga.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 24 (22 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> September 22, 2022 – May 18, 2023</p>
        <p>This season saw the departure of long-time cast member Kelli Giddish (Amanda Rollins), marking the end of a significant era for the squad. The emotional farewell was balanced by the introduction of new faces, ensuring the show's continued evolution. The procedural elements remained incredibly strong, proving that even after more than two decades, the writers could still deliver shocking and compelling mysteries.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 25 (13 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> January 18, 2024 – May 16, 2024</p>
        <p>A milestone 25th season, slightly shortened due to the Hollywood strikes, but packing a massive emotional punch. The show celebrated its incredible longevity by returning to its roots—focusing heavily on the survivors and Benson's unwavering dedication. The introduction of Captain Curry brought fresh tension and new perspectives to the squad room, proving the series can still reinvent itself.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Season 26 (22 Episodes)</h3>
        <p><strong>Aired:</strong> October 3, 2024 – TBD 2025</p>
        <p>The current, ongoing season continues to break records and redefine the television landscape. As the landscape of crime and technology evolves, so too do the cases handled by the SVU. With new detectives fully integrated into the team, the dynamic continues to shift, yet the core mission—advocating for those who have been victimized—remains the beating heart of this legendary institution.</p>
      </div>
